description: Borrowed from Late Latin physicālis, from Latin physica (“study of nature”), from Ancient Greek φυσική (phusikḗ), feminine singular of φυσικός (phusikós, “natural; physical”), from φύσις (phúsis, “origin, birth; nature, quality; form, shape; type, kind”), from φῠ́ω (phúō, “grow”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuH- (“to appear, become, rise up”).

adjectives.description: physical (comparative more physical, superlative most physical)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Pertaining to the field of medicine; medical. [15th–19th c.]
(obsolete) That practises medicine; pertaining to doctors, physicianly. [18th c.]
(obsolete) Medicinal; good for the health, curative, therapeutic. [16th–19th c.]
examples: Phisicall [translating ϕαρμακώδεις (pharmakṓdeis)] herbes, as Helleborum, Lingewort, or Beares foote.

entries.meaning: Pertaining to the world as understood through the senses rather than the mind; tangible, concrete; having to do with the material world. [from 16th c.]
examples: Labour, then, in the physical world, is  […]  employed in putting objects in motion.

entries.meaning: In accordance with the laws of nature; now specifically, pertaining to physics. [from 16th c.]
examples: The substance has a number of interesting physical properties.

entries.meaning: Denoting a map showing natural features of the landscape (compare political). [from 18th c.]
Having to do with the body as opposed to the mind; corporeal,  bodily. [from 18th c.]
examples: Are you feeling any physical effects?

entries.meaning: Involving bodily force or contact; vigorous, aggressive. [from 20th c.]
examples: This team plays a very physical game, so watch out.
How long has it been since your last physical?

entries.meaning: (parapsychology) A physical manifestation of psychic origin, as through ectoplasmic solidification.
